      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Choice Factor in Home Care</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from nursing Prof Arlene Cramer argues that providing waivers for Medicaid money to states for home care does not consider experience and knowledge of community health providers; says there is great need for nurses and home health aides (Jul 8 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Is Home Care Really Working?'' (editorial, July 8):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Is Home Care Really Working?'' (editorial, July 8):</p>
        <p>The problem with providing unmonitored waivers for Medicaid money to states for home care is that it does not consider the experience and knowledge of community health providers. There is a dire need for nurses and home health aides.</p>
        <p>Keeping the elderly in the community without addressing this problem is a recipe for disaster. Let's not force them to bear the burden of our shortsightedness.</p>
        <p>ARLENE CRAMER  Rockville Centre, N.Y., July 8, 2003</p>
        <p>The writer is an assistant professor of nursing at Molloy College.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
